<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>How to Use This Calculator</h2>

  <h3>Convert tab</h3>
  <p>Enter your <strong>annual salary</strong> and <strong>hours per week</strong>. The calculator instantly shows your hourly rate, plus monthly, biweekly, and daily breakdowns. If you have paid vacation, expand <strong>"More options"</strong> and enter your <strong>vacation days</strong> — this reduces the working weeks and shows your true effective hourly rate (which is higher than the nominal one).</p>

  <h3>Compare Offers tab</h3>
  <p>Got two job offers? Enter <strong>Offer A</strong> and <strong>Offer B</strong> — each with salary and expected hours per week. The calculator shows which offer pays more per hour. A $85K job at 45 hours/week might pay less per hour than a $75K job at 40 hours — this tab reveals that.</p>

  <h3>Share your result</h3>
  <p>Every input is encoded in the URL. Click <strong>Share</strong>, send the link to your partner — they'll see your exact numbers. No re-entering, no screenshots.</p>
</section>

<!-- ── FORMULA ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>The Formula</h2>
  <p>The hourly rate is calculated as:</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Hourly Rate = Annual Salary &divide; (Hours per Week &times; Working Weeks per Year)
  </div>
  <p>If you have paid vacation:</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Working Weeks = Weeks per Year &minus; (Vacation Days &divide; 5)
  </div>
  <p>Paid vacation doesn't change your salary, but it changes your <strong>effective hourly rate</strong>. If you earn $75,000 with 4 weeks of paid vacation, your nominal rate is $36.06/hr (52 weeks), but your effective rate is $39.06/hr (48 working weeks) — because you're being paid the same amount for fewer hours of work.</p>
  <p>The <strong>Compare Offers</strong> tab uses the same formula for each offer, so you compare the true hourly value of different salary + hours combinations.</p>
</section>

