<!-- ── FAQ ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Should I use 52 weeks or fewer?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Use 52 for the standard calculation. If you want to see your effective rate excluding vacation time, either reduce weeks to 50 or 48, or enter your paid vacation days under "More options." Both approaches work — the vacation days method is more precise since it handles odd numbers of days.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Does this account for taxes?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        No — this calculates your gross (pre-tax) hourly rate. Tax rates vary by country, state, and filing status. To estimate your after-tax rate, multiply the result by (1 - your effective tax rate). For example, if your effective rate is 25%, multiply by 0.75.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      How do I convert hourly to salary?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Multiply your hourly rate by the hours you work per week, then multiply by 52 (or your working weeks per year). For example, $25/hr × 40 hours × 52 weeks = $52,000/year. Enter this salary into the calculator to see the monthly and biweekly breakdown.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      What about overtime and benefits?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        This calculator uses base salary only. Overtime, bonuses, stock options, and benefits (health insurance, 401k match) aren't included in the hourly rate. For a true comparison between offers, you'd need to estimate the dollar value of benefits. A $75K job with $15K in benefits has a total compensation of $90K — divide that by your working hours for the full picture.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Why is my effective hourly rate higher with vacation?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Because paid vacation means you receive the same annual salary for fewer working hours. If you earn $75,000 and work 52 weeks, your rate is $36.06/hr. With 4 weeks of paid vacation (20 days), you only work 48 weeks but still earn $75,000 — so your effective rate is $39.06/hr. The vacation is essentially extra pay.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

